posts.name: Landon
posts.cooked: When testing around with YAGSL all of the swerve modules would stop and then start causing it to jitter sometimes. When I checked the delay in the code it got up to 26 milliseconds and had lots of paquets lost when it would happen. All of this would spike randomly I tried adjusting the PID with no avail to solving this. It would also happen when running auto.here is the code GitHub - 7657thunderbots/7657SwerveYAGSLCode

posts.name: Technologyman00
posts.cooked: Do you have more information? It’s difficult to understand what is happening and when.

posts.name: Landon
posts.cooked: When driving it around at any speed all of the motors would cut out like it didn’t get input for a cycle.  As soon as it would cut out it would start back up again. It sometimes would happen a few times in a row . Or it would happen just once. There is no real Ryme or reason it does it. You could just be driving foward and then it stops and start or you could be turning while moving and it happens. No CAN bus errors were displayed. It is like the delay of the robot code could be causing problems with the refresh rates of the motor controllers. Also, for context there is both else running in the code except for the drive code.

posts.name: Andrew McBride
posts.cooked: Did you happen to check battery voltage while driving? Or loose power wires to the RIO causing intermittent power loss/brownouts

As a piggy back on that if you’re not using a fully charged new-ish battery this could happen, your current limits could also be met via shorts or improper connections. You can see these effects in DS Logs very easily normally.

posts.name: Josh Sirota
posts.cooked:
We also have been seeing this with our YAGSL bot. It definitely happens with a low battery, but even with a fresh battery, on the driver station it appears to be network dropouts. We found that one of our driver station computers seems to do it less than the other one, though it’s not really scientific.

Last year, my team (a different team) had a similar problem with network issues. Turned out to be a process running on the RoboRIO (FRC_NetcommDaemon) was running away with the CPU for reasons no one knows. Killing the process it fixed it. Never happened during comps, only during testing, never fully resolved. Our theory was that something we were doing in our robot code was overtaxing the network and this particular FRC thing couldn’t handle it, but we never figured out what it was. This year, we haven’t had a chance to check if it’s the same thing or not.
